title: Medically Retired Air Force Signals Intelligence Analyst
name: Tom Berdine
summary: I was in the Air force for 16 years from 1985-2001. The full 16 years I served as a Signals intelligence (SIGINT) Analyst for the National Security Agency (NSA). I was assigned to remote facilities around the world: 1985-1986: Biloxi Mississippi for initial Morse Code Operator training; 1986-1988: Misawa Air Base, Japan. 1988-1989: Iraklion, Air Station, Island of Crete, Greece. . 1989-1992 Misawa Air Base, Japan for the second time. NOTE: In 1996 I won the GOLD Medal in the Air Intelligence Agencies annual SENSOR OLYMPICS, a world-wide competition identifying the “TOP” personnel in various career fields. 1997-1998 Selected for Advanced SIGNAL Analysis Training at Pensacola Naval Air Station, Florida; 1998-2000 Stationed at Wright Patterson Air Force Base, National Air Intelligence Center (NAIC). 2000-2001 Stationed at Kunia Regional SIGINT Operations Center (KRSOC) on Oahu, Hawaii. 2001 Medically retired from the US Air Force with 80% of my base pay for Depression & Parkinson’s disease. Awarded 80% disability from the Veterans administration. 2002 Attended the University of Phoenix via a $15,000 grant from the VA. Attended the Microsoft Certified Systems Engineer (MCSE) Certification course. 2002 Hired by the Department Of Energy, National Nuclear Transportation Agencies’, Office Of Secure Transportation on Kirtland AFB. 2003 Bought my first home. 2005 Placed on full disability by my contractor and received full time disability. 2006 Applied for and received full Social Security Disability 2007 Awarded 100% disability from the Veterans administration.

description: My main role is as a software engineer. I have been a major contributor to the development of NRL's Specific Emitter Identification (SEI) capability since 1981 when I was employed by Quest Tech which was acquired by CACI in 1996. I am the resident historian for the Specific Emitter Identification program at NRL. I have written signal processing, GUI, and relational database interface software. In addition to my programming duties, I managed a contract for CACI with the U.S. Naval Research Laboratory. During my twelve years of service I have been responsible for directing my staff and handling performance reviews, interfacing with the government project manager and the contract officer's representative (COR), and managing the writing of the proposals. In the twelve years at CACI I have worked mainly in Visual C++ using the Microsoft Foundation Classes (MFC) and the Standard Template Library (STL). I also worked with the SQL databases MySQL and SQLite, and earlier with an Access type database using Codebase. I also did graphics work using the Pro-Essentials graphics package, and database management work using Rogue Wave's Objective Grid package. Through my work at NRL; I have had contact with the SEI community in general. This included supporting installation and training at Navy and NSA sites around the globe. It also included consultation and system integration with General Dynamics, and Lockheed Martin.

description: Designed and wrote a Particle Distribution Blending and Surface Area program that will calculate a specified or optimized blend of up to 8 particle distributions, as compared to a Farris, Furnas or specified particle distribution. The optimum blend is calculated by setting the derivative of the RMS error function with respect to the percent of each distribution equal to zero, and then solving n simultaneous linear equations. An RMS error is computed as a measure of conformity of the new composite distribution to the ideal distribution. Surface area calculations are also reported. This software is a strategic ARC tool. Designed and wrote a Statistical Environmental Database for the analysis and storage of environmental soil, water and air field data. It calculates a Behrens-Fisher t-test for significant variation from a baseline. Time-trend regression analysis is also conducted. Database search/retrieval and table plotting are also provided. The software saves Atlantic Research Corporation 50K+ in annual statistician consulting fees. Designed and wrote software for calculating the oxygen/fuel ratio of solid rocket propellants containing metallic species, by solving a series of simultaneous linear equations for the oxygen/fuel ratio requested. Solid rocket propellant chemist involving the processing of rocket propellant formulations with acceptable ballistics and physical properties. IR&D syntheses of Methylene Dioxyammonium Dinitrate (DOAN), 3-Nitro-1,2,4-Triazol-5-One (NTO), and Hexabenzylhexaazaiso-wurtzitane. Performed Strategic Defense Initiative (SDI) research as a propellant chemist, developing a Kinetic Energy Weapon (KEW 2.5) in a specially built laboratory. Principle technical coordinator for three material and component aging programs for the Trident Missile Post Boost control system. Conducted statistical data analyses and technical report writing, with verbal presentations to Lockheed Missiles and Space Company and the U.S. Navy.

title: Principal Systems Engineer
name: Paul Nix
description: Six weeks after I joined this little company (intent on bringing adaptive beam forming to the commercial cellular market) the parent organization, Raytheon, announced that it didn't want to be in the business and put us up for sale (so no more funding). As a result I spend much of my time evaluating a satellite modem technology for terrestrial applications (Raytheon had laid off a small satellite modem development group and through my boss I was asked to investigate the hardware to see if it could be used). There was also still life in the adaptive beamforming work and I worked with the realtime software developers to provide signal analysis of commercial cellular signals (in support of this effort I installed an active rooftop antenna array). After our manufacturing group (they'd been building an amplified antenna for a major cellular manufacturer) was laid off, and with the Engineering team beginning to drift off to other companies, I decided that I'd better do the same.

name: Paul Nix
description: This was my first job out of college and it still makes me smile. The only thing that could have made it better would have been to come along a few years earlier so that I could have worked directly for Collins Radio (they were acquired by Rockwell-International in the mid-1970s). I traveled all over the U.S. installing, turning-up and trouble-shooting Rockwell-Collins digital microwave radios. I worked on mountain tops in New Mexico and Wyoming, saw the Northern Lights from Wisconsin, swung from a bosun's chair part-way up an AT&T tower in the hills of eastern Kentucky, and travelled much of the Ozark Mountains. A trip to Caracas enabled me to fix the digital control system used by the Venezuelan Oil Ministry on their Collins microwave radio system. My boss once asked me "Would you go to Khartoum?" but I was enough of a student of history and geography to politely demur (I'm no Gordon). If it needed to get done ... as a Collins Field Engineer I got to do it. (I've 'swept' waveguide, tuned I.F.s, aligned microwave paths, and, on a back road in the Ozarks of southern Missouri, I 'shooed' wandering cattle back into the pasture where they belonged.)

summary: I’m not sure which word is more important to me: Serial or Entrepreneur, but I try to embody both and help others to do the same. These days, I’m committed to helping speakers, coaches, trainers and educators increase their reach, and their revenue, using automated software systems. From 2000 to 2010, I built and ran a very successful software development firm whose focus was on creating custom platforms for small- to medium-sized businesses (from 6 to 8 figures in annual revenues). We covered everything from eCommerce to Human Resources, CRM to Inventory Management… and beyond. Now we’re making those tools, and the lessons we’ve learned, available to everyone who might benefit from them. The majority of our current work is in digital media sales (online courses, membership programs, ecommerce, etc.). However, my first business, and my first love, was being a magician. I started making money by performing when I was 10 years old and eventually paid for my entire college education by doing shows for company parties and trade shows. While it’s not longer a revenue stream for me, I still have the privilege of performing a week a year at the world famous Magic Castle in Hollywood, as well as several command performances at venues in Las Vegas. I’m also faculty on what the BBC called “The world’s most prestigious magic school.” The rest of my background is in technology. My undergraduate work was in robotics. Grad school got me into statistics and modeling. My only “real job” was for Motorola, performing advanced statistical predictions for their satellite & space projects. In my spare time, I invest in real estate, train Shao-lin kung fu and travel the world with my amazing wife and friends.
description: Providing tools and training to automate, improve and analyze revenue generation for speakers, educators, trainers and coaches.

description: "Infrared Dust Emission in Luminous Infrared Galaxy IC883: Weak AGN or Star-burst?" • Investigated radiative, mechanical, and thermal energy transport processes associated with luminous infrared galaxy IC883, and other galaxies in the GOALS (Great Observatory All Sky LIRG Survey) catalog. Identiﬁed and characterized various components of the far infrared spectral energy distribution (warm dust, polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons, and other non-thermal components). Used various software packages to quantify these features (Python and Image Reduction Analysis Facility) using archival data from space-based telescopes Spitzer, Hubble, and Herschel along with ground based radio and interferometry data. This research was funded by the National Science Foundation (NSF) under grant AST-1004583. Attended ”Star Formation and Gas Reservoirs in Nearby Groups and Clusters” conference in Schenectady, NY

description: "Analog/Digital Signal Analysis in Physical Instrumentation and Detectors" • In this research I built and operated threshold circuits based on a basic Schmitt- trigger design architecture which derived inputs from various physical sensors. I used an Arduino micro-controller which sent the output of the sensors to the serial port of a computer, which allowed me to store and process data from the circuits. I used various computer codes (in C) to set thresholds and conditional levels for the sensors. I used many diﬀerent sensors including; sharp infrared IR range sensors (GP2D12), LM35 analog linear temperature sensors (DFR0023), analog ambient light sensors (DFR0026), digital magnetic sensors (DFR0033), analog carbon monoxide sensors (MQ7-SEN0132), and infrared emitters and detectors. Through this research I established a strong understanding of the physical basis of electronics & circuits, micro-controller theory and operation, and analog-to- digital conversion methods.

description: "Observing Extinction Eﬀects due to Bok Globules with the SARA 0.9m Telescope" • Conducted research on optical depth and dynamics of dust particles in the ISM (interstellar medium). Modeled the transport properties of electromagnetic radiation as it passes through these and other media (radiative transport). Performed several observing runs at Kitt Peak National Observatory in Arizona for several Bok Globules in the local Milky Way. Developed familiarity with the basics of observational and theoretical astronomical methods and procedures. Re- search funded by the National Science Foundation (NSF) under grant NSF AST- 1004872. Published a paper with my research mentor Dieter H. Hartmann and his PhD student Adria Updike which can be found on the NASA/SAO database (see Publications).

description: "Characterizing Thermal Noise in Astronomical Charge Coupled Devices" • Developed methods to probe the linearity of thermal noise in the Apogee Alta charge-coupled device (CCD) at the SARA 0.9m telescope in Tuscon, AZ. Developed an understanding of the solid- state physics underlying differences between various CCD types: deep-depletion, orthogonal transfer, and multi-pinned phase CCDs etc. I implemented IDL codes to "stack" images and perform in-depth analysis involving dark exposures and bias frame subtractions. Determined a nonlinear trend in thermal noise generation within the system and began working on methods to reduce/account for this noise to fully exploit the CCD‘s capabilities.

title: IT Help Desk Administrator
name: Dennis Maxwell
description: As the Helpdesk Analyst /Technical Lead my primary responsibility is to assist the MIS Director in day to day operations. Daily duties include; monitoring the helpdesk, assigning and prioritizing tickets, administrating and maintaining local and remote servers / computers along with the local area network (LAN) for 100+ local users, and 16 remote retail stores. A major part of my job is to evaluate, test, and recommend hardware or software to improve operations/production. As a cost reduction and simplification of our IT infrastructure I implemented the use of virtual computing desktop servers using; (NComputing software) replacing over 60 personal computers with plans to replace more in the near future. The implication of virtual computing has cut IT operational cost by 10-15 %.
